{
  "texts": [
    "Existing ethical regulations governing research do not apply to the routine deployment of AI to improve operational efficiency or to reduce the cognitive load of healthcare providers which are not considered health products despite risk of harm to patient outcomes, raising significant ethical concerns 8, 9.",
    "Although technologies are often intended to enhance workflows and throughputs and reduce clinician burnout, emerging evidence suggests that LLM use can lead to unintended harm.",
    "For example, outputs from LLMs, such as OpenAI's ChatGPT, which uses GPT-4 (Generative Pre-trained Transformer 4) 10 -one of the most advanced text-based generative AI models 11 -can be biased by patient demographics 12, leading to stereotypical presentations and potentially impacting the quality and equity of care 13.",
    "For instance, assessments and plans generated by ChatGPT have been linked to recommendations for more expensive procedures, exacerbating healthcare disparities and costs 12.",
    "Additionally, clinical documentation produced by LLMs influences clinician decision-making through anchoring and automation biases 14, 15."
  ]
}